<font color="#FF0000">THE NEED FOR SPEED</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 20 22:39:16 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
MTF,<br><br>
The first time I went from the 60-knot category to the 1000-knot machines was like being thrown from a twenty-story building and then wondering if I could learn to fly.  It is like that that other thing more of it is just more fun.  The only problem was projecting your horizon and thinking at 1000 knots.  You would fit nicely, just remember until you really learn keep your feet off the pedals except for steering.  Have you ever been kicked in the ass so hard with acceleration that you suffer vertigo?  2 meters off the burner cans under your buddy at 600 +.  Flying is just &quot;plane&quot; fun no matter what the vehicle.  When you talk to her and she talks back you have made it.<br><br>
I worked and flew as a civilian with the Top Guns of the Navy, Marines, Air Force, Canadians, and some of the foreign forces.  These guys like the go fast stuff.  We all did.  You and I know it is not as loose as the movie Top Gun.  You never buzz the tower these days and you may only buzz the carrier with the Air Boss's permission.  If the marshal pattern is empty he will usually give you permission as long as you keep it under the mach. Destroyers and Aegis is fair game as long as you stay out of the bubble.  Kick butt.  The crazier the better. <br><br>
The problem arises from the massive curtailment of training hours and sorties.  Less free play. Not as much fun as it use to be and all flyboys must do other duty to make enough rank to stay to retirement.  The lure of the Airlines is a big factor.<br><br>
Top gun boys can be gone from home a lot, which strains that life.  The Air Force is no longer weekend warriors.  Actually schedule the weekends off.  As a matter of fact most guys not at sea get the weekend off and very few holidays for work.  Pilots have the most leisure work schedule of any service member.  Where can you get paid these days for having fun?  Poor babies.  Peacetime does change the breed.<br><br>
We never had it so good.  By the way Ed that bonus doesn't guarantee your stay to retirement.  Couple that with the eroding benefits and the incentive leaves.  The only ones who stay are those hooked on the rush.  Ain't nothing like it.<br><br>
Training to the instructor level costs a great deal more than $6,000,000.  A good year could burn 3/4 to 1 million in fuel per man just training depending on the aircraft type. (heavy pipe burners.)<br><br>
More, but enough for now.<br>

